cover imageIn this article, we’ll build a simple lexer in Go and understand how source code is converted into tokens.
What happens when we run our code?
Lexer
It reads our code character by character and groups it into tokens. It doesn’t care whether the code is valid. It only converts the input into tokens. That’s exactly what we’re going to build in this article
Syntax Analysis
The parser takes the tokens and builds an AST (Abstract Syntax Tree). It checks whether the tokens follow the grammar of the language. If they don’t, we get a syntax error.
Semantic Analysis
This checks whether the code makes logical sense
Execution
After semantic analysis, the language implementation either interprets the AST directly or translates it into another representation, such as bytecode or machine code.
In this article, we’ll write a simple lexer
Before we start, one disclaimer. This lexer is not perfect and there are some edge cases. I know there are better ways to write it. I wrote this on my own to understand how lexers work, and I’ll explain the logic I used.
This lexer only supports identifiers made up of letters and integer numbers. It doesn’t handle floating-point numbers, identifiers like hello123 or my_var, or string literals. The goal is to understand the basic idea of lexing.
