Now, let’s define Lexer struct in lexer.go
package maintype Lexer struct {
input string
position int
nextPosition int
ch byte
}
Fields of Lexer struct

• input -> will store the whole input string in this field

• position -> points to the current index of the input string

• nextPosition -> points to the next index that needs to be read in the input string

• ch -> will store the input character that is currently being read
Now, let’s define some methods. One of them will initialize the Lexer, similar to a constructor.
lexer.go
func (l*Lexer) readChar(){
// updates the position
if(l.nextPosition>=len(l.input)){
l.ch = 0
}else {
l.ch = l.input[l.nextPosition]
}
l.position = l.nextPosition
l.nextPosition = l.position+1
}func NewLexer(input string)*Lexer{
var lex Lexer = Lexer{
input: input,
}
lex.readChar()
return &lex
}
func NewToken(ty string, literal string)tokens.Token{
return tokens.Token{Type: ty, Literal: literal}
}
The NewLexerfunction takes the input from stdin, initializes the Lexer struct, and returns a pointer to it.
Same as NewLexer function, the NewToken function takes the type and literal and returns a token
The readChar function updates the current position of the lexer. It reads the next character from the input string, stores it inch, updates position to the current index, and moves nextPosition one step ahead.
now, in the main.go
var lex *Lexer = NewLexer(input) var token []tokens.Token = make([]tokens.Token, 0, 10);
Initialize the lexer and create a slice to store all the generated tokens
Let’s define other methods for the lexer
to skip white spaces
func (t *Lexer) skipWhiteSpaces(){
for t.ch==' ' || t.ch == '\t' || t.ch == '\n' || t.ch == '\r'{
t.readChar()
}
}This skips the white spaces, tabs, and new lines from the input string
When one of these whitespace characters is found, we call readChar to move to the next character
Now, let’s write methods to read the identifiers, numbers, and identify the type of those
func (l *Lexer)readIdentifier()string{
position:=l.position for unicode.IsLetter(rune(l.ch)){
l.readChar()
}
return l.input[position:l.position]
}
func (l *Lexer)readNumber()string{
position:=l.position
for unicode.IsDigit(rune(l.ch)){
l.readChar()
}
return l.input[position:l.position]
}
func identType(iden string)tokens.Token{
switch iden{
case "const":
return NewToken(tokens.CONST, iden)
case "let":
return NewToken(tokens.LET, iden)
case "return":
return NewToken(tokens.RETURN, iden)
default:
return NewToken(tokens.IDENT, iden)
}
}
the readIdentifier method, reads characters until it finds something that isn’t a letter
readNumberreads consecutive digits and returns them as a string
in the identType, checks whether the string is a keyword or a user-defined identifier
Now, NextTokenfunction and peek char

func (l *Lexer) NextToken() tokens.Token {
var token tokens.Token
l.skipWhiteSpaces()
switch l.ch{
case '=':
if l.peekChar() == '=' {
token = NewToken(tokens.DOUBLEEQ, "==")
l.readChar()
} else {
token = NewToken(tokens.ASSIGN, "=")
}
case '!':
if l.peekChar() == '=' {
token = NewToken(tokens.NOTEQUAL, "!=")
l.readChar()
} else {
token = NewToken(tokens.EXCLAIM, "!")
} case '+':
token= NewToken(tokens.PLUS, string(l.ch))
case '(':
token= NewToken(tokens.LPAREN, string(l.ch))
case ')':
token= NewToken(tokens.RPAREN, string(l.ch))
case '{':
token= NewToken(tokens.LCURLY, string(l.ch))
case '}':
token= NewToken(tokens.RCURLY, string(l.ch))
case ';':
token= NewToken(tokens.SEMICOLAN, string(l.ch))
case ',':
token = NewToken(tokens.COMMA, string(l.ch))
case 0:
token= NewToken(tokens.EOF, "")
default:
if unicode.IsLetter(rune(l.ch)){
token:=l.readIdentifier()
return identType(token)
}else if unicode.IsDigit(rune(l.ch)){
number := l.readNumber()
return NewToken(tokens.INT, number)
}else{
token = NewToken(tokens.ILLEGAL, string(l.ch))
}
}
l.readChar()
return token
}
func (l *Lexer) peekChar()byte {
if l.nextPosition>=len(l.input){
return 0
}
return l.input[l.nextPosition]
}
The NextToken function reads the current character and checks what token it is using the switch statement. If it finds a single-character token like + or (.It creates the token directly. If it finds an identifier or a number, it calls readIdentifier or readNumber to read the complete value. After creating the token, it calls readChar to move to the next character in the input.
peekChar looks at the next character without moving the current position.
For example, if the input is = or +, they are single-character tokens, so we don't need peekChar. But what if the input is == or !=? When we read the first character, we need to know whether the next character is also =. That's why we use peekChar. It lets us look at the next character without moving the current position.
